now than the two years before.

00:12:16.940 --> 00:12:19.370
And that's what we basically
prepared for in the last half

00:12:19.370 --> 00:12:19.970
a year.

00:12:19.970 --> 00:12:21.803
IKY SANDORFFY: That
said, you often optimize

00:12:21.803 --> 00:12:24.266
during that period for
long term retention?

00:12:24.266 --> 00:12:26.390
JENS BEGEMANN: We optimize
for long term retention.

00:12:26.390 --> 00:12:28.580
I mean, one sentence
I say is, OK

00:12:28.580 --> 00:12:30.410
you will lose a certain
amount of people

00:12:30.410 --> 00:12:31.460
during your first week.

00:12:31.460 --> 00:12:32.834
They may not like
the theme, they

00:12:32.834 --> 00:12:34.640
may not like the
genre, but those

00:12:34.640 --> 00:12:37.400
who are still with you
after a week you really want

00:12:37.400 --> 00:12:39.164
to keep in the long run.

00:12:39.164 --> 00:12:40.580
You really still
want to have them

00:12:40.580 --> 00:12:43.050
after you that was the
mindset on content production.

00:12:43.050 --> 00:12:45.470
IKY SANDORFFY: So from day
seven to day 28 retention,

00:12:45.470 --> 00:12:47.660
you expect a minimal drop
off in order to justify.

00:12:47.660 --> 00:12:49.910
JENS BEGEMANN: Actually,
with our hidden object games,

00:12:49.910 --> 00:12:53.720
we've now changed, our reporting
system to measure day 720

00:12:53.720 --> 00:12:55.772
retention because these
games are really about--

00:12:55.772 --> 00:12:56.730
IKY SANDORFFY: Day 720?

00:12:56.730 --> 00:12:58.354
JENS BEGEMANN: Yes,
two-year retention.

00:12:58.354 --> 00:13:01.060
So we measure two-year
retention for cohorts

00:13:01.060 --> 00:13:03.839
because long term retention
is everything for these games.

00:13:03.839 --> 00:13:05.630
IKY SANDORFFY: That's
a good segue actually

00:13:05.630 --> 00:13:08.390
to move on to George.

00:13:08.390 --> 00:13:10.250
You've been running
your hit games

00:13:10.250 --> 00:13:12.350
for the last couple
of years with King,

00:13:12.350 --> 00:13:16.010
running the now very
famous "Candy Crush

00:13:16.010 --> 00:13:18.570
Saga" and the entire franchise.

00:13:18.570 --> 00:13:22.430
I had figured you also optimize
for the long term retention.

00:13:22.430 --> 00:13:26.330
I'm wondering how you guys make
the decision between launching

00:13:26.330 --> 00:13:28.970
a new franchise, to launching
a content update on one

00:13:28.970 --> 00:13:30.410
of your existing titles.

00:13:30.410 --> 00:13:31.760
GEORGE ABRAMOVICI: OK.

00:13:31.760 --> 00:13:35.600
Basically, we had to
think about this strategy

00:13:35.600 --> 00:13:38.510
around a few years ago when we
realized that "Candy Crush" is

00:13:38.510 --> 00:13:41.690
here to stay for a long time.

00:13:41.690 --> 00:13:44.400
We decided to build
two parallel tracks,

00:13:44.400 --> 00:13:46.940
and one is keep working
on "Candy Crush"

00:13:46.940 --> 00:13:48.720
and improve the game
and keep it fresh.

00:13:48.720 --> 00:13:51.000
We are adding new
levels, updating

00:13:51.000 --> 00:13:56.120
big extensions and new
content every second week.

00:13:56.120 --> 00:13:59.450
Then, we also say we need
to also do something else,

00:13:59.450 --> 00:14:01.050
so we followed this same--

00:14:01.050 --> 00:14:02.240
these two tracks.

00:14:02.240 --> 00:14:04.250
Investing in existing
games and also

00:14:04.250 --> 00:14:06.500
working on launching new ones--

00:14:06.500 --> 00:14:09.690
can be sister titles or can be
sequels to the original one.

00:14:09.690 --> 00:14:11.409
But also new IPs as well.

00:14:11.409 --> 00:14:13.200
IKY SANDORFFY: When
you do launch a sequel,

00:14:13.200 --> 00:14:14.330
do you prefer--

00:14:14.330 --> 00:14:17.180
essentially, are you taking
existing game teams or existing

00:14:17.180 --> 00:14:19.940
stuff from the game teams in
order to develop that sequel,

00:14:19.940 --> 00:14:22.820
or an extra dimension
where you actually

00:14:22.820 --> 00:14:24.840
hired a completely
separate team to continue?

00:14:24.840 --> 00:14:26.090
GEORGE ABRAMOVICI: It's a mix.

00:14:26.090 --> 00:14:28.700
We also learned we need to use
the expertise from the people

00:14:28.700 --> 00:14:30.380
that worked on previous games.

00:14:30.380 --> 00:14:33.230
Some of them already know
how to build certain stuff,

00:14:33.230 --> 00:14:35.050
and they're needed
in the new team,

00:14:35.050 --> 00:14:39.170
but we also have
new things as well.

00:14:39.170 --> 00:14:40.810
IKY SANDORFFY: Pretty cool.

00:14:40.810 --> 00:14:43.850
It's working, clearly.

00:14:43.850 --> 00:14:47.660
Definitely something
we can learn from.

00:14:47.660 --> 00:14:52.010
Back to you, Jens, actually,
I wanted to ask specifically

00:14:52.010 --> 00:14:54.740
about the inverse
of "June's Journey,"

00:14:54.740 --> 00:14:57.260
of what we've just discussed,
of an experience you've

00:14:57.260 --> 00:15:00.630
had as developing a game with
a relatively long schedule

00:15:00.630 --> 00:15:03.652
and production cycle,
and where you ended up

00:15:03.652 --> 00:15:05.610
with a decision of saying
this is not worth it.

00:15:05.610 --> 00:15:08.220
We should actually roll back and
change, and move the research

00:15:08.220 --> 00:15:10.320
to something else.

00:15:10.320 --> 00:15:11.880
Deciding to kill
or roll back here.

00:15:11.880 --> 00:15:15.030
JENS BEGEMANN: Yeah, we question
our productions all the time

00:15:15.030 --> 00:15:17.410
and we actually stop
games at different stages.

00:15:17.410 --> 00:15:20.970
So just a couple of days
ago, we stopped a project

00:15:20.970 --> 00:15:23.790
that was already full
scale into production,

00:15:23.790 --> 00:15:26.040
over 20 people team,
but it was still

00:15:26.040 --> 00:15:28.860
over a year away from launch.

00:15:28.860 --> 00:15:33.090
We saw too many risks
and in the end decided,

00:15:33.090 --> 00:15:35.280
OK we'll stop this.

00:15:35.280 --> 00:15:38.130
Not everything was shaping up
to give a very clear picture

00:15:38.130 --> 00:15:40.770
of "this will be awesome"
because just good is not enough

00:15:40.770 --> 00:15:41.340
anymore.

00:15:41.340 --> 00:15:42.930
On this market,
you have to be one

00:15:42.930 --> 00:15:46.290
of the best or maybe the best
in your genre to have a chance.

00:15:46.290 --> 00:15:49.770
So that was really based
on relatively early stage,

00:15:49.770 --> 00:15:54.350
and based on play tests
and subjective evaluation.

00:15:54.350 --> 00:15:57.660
But we also stopped a project
in May that was in soft launch,

00:15:57.660 --> 00:15:59.910
based on retention metrics.

00:15:59.910 --> 00:16:01.690
Day one day three
retention was good

00:16:01.690 --> 00:16:06.390
but then day seven, the drop
off of retention was too strong.

00:16:06.390 --> 00:16:09.810
We just stopped that in
relatively early stages

00:16:09.810 --> 00:16:10.560
of soft launch.

00:16:10.560 --> 00:16:12.720
IKY SANDORFFY: So those were two
separate cycles, if you will.

00:16:12.720 --> 00:16:13.970
One subjective playtest.

00:16:13.970 --> 00:16:16.620
JENS BEGEMANN: One very
subjective playtest,

00:16:16.620 --> 00:16:18.390
over a year away from launch.

00:16:18.390 --> 00:16:21.660
The second one was after a
couple of months of soft launch

00:16:21.660 --> 00:16:22.974
based on metrics.

00:16:22.974 --> 00:16:25.140
IKY SANDORFFY: So, even
after the subjective measure

00:16:25.140 --> 00:16:27.620
that we figured out it might
not hold up, the quality,

00:16:27.620 --> 00:16:28.580
you still went--

00:16:28.580 --> 00:16:30.330
JENS BEGEMANN: This
market is super tough,

00:16:30.330 --> 00:16:34.030
I don't meet any developer
who says it's easy.

00:16:34.030 --> 00:16:35.470
I never meet them.

00:16:35.470 --> 00:16:37.000
So it's super, super tough.

00:16:37.000 --> 00:16:39.750
You have to be one of the
best, and therefore the bar

00:16:39.750 --> 00:16:44.280
is crazy high, and you
have to be quite ruthless.

00:16:44.280 --> 00:16:46.470
Only if you're completely
convinced that this will

00:16:46.470 --> 00:16:49.020
be great, you should continue.

00:16:49.020 --> 00:16:51.390
If it's, oh, this is pretty
good, that's not enough.

00:16:51.390 --> 00:16:52.830
That's not acceptable.

00:16:52.830 --> 00:16:54.780
SAAD CHOUDRI: Can
I ask a question?

00:16:54.780 --> 00:16:58.280
Because it's probably more
relevant for the room,

00:16:58.280 --> 00:17:01.080
but everyone talks about
the retention metrics.

00:17:01.080 --> 00:17:02.130
What is your bar?

00:17:02.130 --> 00:17:04.500
You said you guys set
a bar, what's your bar?

00:17:04.500 --> 00:17:07.510
Above the 40, 20, 10, what
are you guys looking at?

00:17:07.510 --> 00:17:11.339
JENS BEGEMANN: What we do
is we look at days played.

00:17:11.339 --> 00:17:14.280
For every install, how
many days on average

00:17:14.280 --> 00:17:16.117
does that person
play over the year?

00:17:16.117 --> 00:17:16.950
SAAD CHOUDRI: Right.

00:17:16.950 --> 00:17:19.020
JENS BEGEMANN:
Over the next year.

00:17:19.020 --> 00:17:22.109
That number can be high because
long-term retention is amazing,

00:17:22.109 --> 00:17:24.119
or that number can be
high because everybody

00:17:24.119 --> 00:17:27.359
plays for the first few
weeks and then drops off.

00:17:27.359 --> 00:17:31.290
There, something in the ballpark
of days played of 30 to 40

00:17:31.290 --> 00:17:32.580
is good.

00:17:32.580 --> 00:17:35.280
You have 100 installs
and then on average they

00:17:35.280 --> 00:17:37.440
play 30 or 40 days
during the year.

00:17:37.440 --> 00:17:39.420
But obviously, monetization
is also important.

00:17:39.420 --> 00:17:41.045
SAAD CHOUDRI: That's
30 to 40 sessions.

00:17:42.610 --> 00:17:44.452
Separate days.

00:17:44.452 --> 00:17:46.410
JENS BEGEMANN: Obviously,
out of those hundreds

00:17:46.410 --> 00:17:49.500
installs, most of them play one.

00:17:49.500 --> 00:17:52.800
Because if you have
50% day one retention,

00:17:52.800 --> 00:17:55.190
that's already cutting.

00:17:55.190 --> 00:17:56.910
Yeah that's the way
we look at it now,

00:17:56.910 --> 00:17:58.140
because we think numbers.

00:17:58.140 --> 00:18:00.990
Like, hey, day 30 retention
needs to be about 15%,

00:18:00.990 --> 00:18:07.020
or day 30 retention needs to
be 20%, it's just one number.

00:18:07.020 --> 00:18:09.294
You look at the
whole dropoff rate.

00:18:09.294 --> 00:18:10.960
SAAD CHOUDRI: You use
the amount of days

00:18:10.960 --> 00:18:12.960
that people play to figure
out your calculation.

00:18:12.960 --> 00:18:15.840
OK, I think that a lot of
people are moving towards that.

00:18:15.840 --> 00:18:19.060
JENS BEGEMANN: We making
LTV predictions, basically.

00:18:19.060 --> 00:18:22.260
SAAD CHOUDRI: Yeah, that's
what I hope many people do.

00:18:22.260 --> 00:18:24.840
JENS BEGEMANN: No, you have to
predict LTV during soft launch

00:18:24.840 --> 00:18:25.881
and see where it ends up.

00:18:25.881 --> 00:18:29.370
IKY SANDORFFY: That actually
brings up a really good point,

00:18:29.370 --> 00:18:34.740
Saad, and specifically to you
and the recent launch of "War

00:18:34.740 --> 00:18:38.790
Wings" and now just a little
bit surprised that we're almost

00:18:38.790 --> 00:18:39.880
running out of time.

00:18:39.880 --> 00:18:42.570
But just to quickly just talk
about the "War Wings" launch

00:18:42.570 --> 00:18:44.570
because you really have
done something different

00:18:44.570 --> 00:18:45.870
from your recent launches.

00:18:45.870 --> 00:18:49.080
SAAD CHOUDRI: Yeah, we
went a little bit outside

00:18:49.080 --> 00:18:52.500
of what people perceive as
our traditional comfort zone,

00:18:52.500 --> 00:18:58.080
where we really launched a
fully 3D dog fighting game.

00:18:58.080 --> 00:19:01.705
We, like Jens, talked
about the dress rehearsal

00:19:01.705 --> 00:19:04.080
in one territory, so we had
already done the soft launch,

00:19:04.080 --> 00:19:06.540
and then we essentially
focused on doing

00:19:06.540 --> 00:19:12.510
a full, almost global
launch-esque campaign in one

00:19:12.510 --> 00:19:13.090
territory.

00:19:13.090 --> 00:19:14.400
We did that in the UK.

00:19:14.400 --> 00:19:18.990
We did your full UA that
you would do, we did TV,

00:19:18.990 --> 00:19:22.320
we did cinema, we
did a lot of things.

00:19:22.320 --> 00:19:25.740
We worked with the platforms who
supported us on this endeavor

00:19:25.740 --> 00:19:29.640
to try and see
what that would do.

00:19:29.640 --> 00:19:34.650
Soft launch can give you a false
sense of security sometimes.

00:19:34.650 --> 00:19:37.440
I think a lot of people, and
a lot of product managers,

00:19:37.440 --> 00:19:41.730
and a lot og UA
teams will almost

00:19:41.730 --> 00:19:43.664
do too well in soft
launch because they'll

00:19:43.664 --> 00:19:45.330
have targeted the
users that they really

00:19:45.330 --> 00:19:47.160
want and the metrics
start looking good.

00:19:47.160 --> 00:19:50.580
Then you wonder why they haven't
scaled when you go into global.

00:19:50.580 --> 00:19:53.884
They'll be like oh,
it's the featuring.

00:19:53.884 --> 00:19:55.800
You get loads of these
casual audiences, guys.

00:19:55.800 --> 00:19:59.244
I know you guys hear it, we
might as well talk about it.

00:19:59.244 --> 00:20:00.910
So why we did that
is just to really get

00:20:00.910 --> 00:20:04.870
a good sense of what that
would do on a global stage.

00:20:04.870 --> 00:20:07.930
It's proven to be
successful, because it

00:20:07.930 --> 00:20:09.914
replicated onto the
global launch, when

00:20:09.914 --> 00:20:10.830
we pushed it out live.

00:20:10.830 --> 00:20:12.040
IKY SANDORFFY: Would that
work for "Homescapes"?

00:20:12.040 --> 00:20:14.440
Or would that have been a
good strategy for "Homescapes"

00:20:14.440 --> 00:20:15.160
as well?

00:20:15.160 --> 00:20:17.710
Doubling down on one
country and going all in,

00:20:17.710 --> 00:20:19.840
or do you rather go
for a global launch

00:20:19.840 --> 00:20:22.570
and then really see down the
line where you need to focus?

00:20:22.570 --> 00:20:24.111
SERGEI ZAITSEV: It's
a good question.

00:20:26.050 --> 00:20:28.434
We think that the
definition of a soft launch

00:20:28.434 --> 00:20:30.350
should be different,
dependent on the context.

00:20:30.350 --> 00:20:33.280
So if you go to the very
competitive crowded space

00:20:33.280 --> 00:20:37.750
like mystery genre,
then then it should

00:20:37.750 --> 00:20:42.700
release on the soft launch very
highly polished product, which

00:20:42.700 --> 00:20:45.887
is pretty ready for
the commercial launch.

00:20:45.887 --> 00:20:47.470
If you are missing
any of the features

00:20:47.470 --> 00:20:49.540
that other competitors
have in the market,

00:20:49.540 --> 00:20:52.630
then we will not make it.

00:20:52.630 --> 00:20:54.040
You will not make it.

00:20:54.040 --> 00:20:57.490
On the soft launch, we don't
test any mechanics or concepts.

00:20:57.490 --> 00:21:01.900
We already are sure that
the game is in good shape.

00:21:01.900 --> 00:21:07.300
But what they're testing is
retentions, monetization,

00:21:07.300 --> 00:21:10.510
technical side, that
nothing crashes.

00:21:10.510 --> 00:21:15.460
And then we also test
the difficulty curve,

00:21:15.460 --> 00:21:20.950
which is gender equality.

00:21:20.950 --> 00:21:26.050
We soft launch in Canada,
usually, and Australia.

00:21:26.050 --> 00:21:28.930
We believe that
these metrics are

00:21:28.930 --> 00:21:30.840
pretty reliable for
the commercial launch.

00:21:35.010 --> 00:21:38.600
The period for which we soft
launch, it depends on the game.

00:21:38.600 --> 00:21:44.660
And for "Gardenscapes," we soft
launched it for several months.

00:21:44.660 --> 00:21:48.560
And "Homescapes", we kept it
in soft launch for one month.

00:21:52.920 --> 00:21:55.230
We can rely on these numbers.

00:21:55.230 --> 00:21:56.880
IKY SANDORFFY: But
it clearly worked.

00:21:56.880 --> 00:21:59.640
All of you guys have been
really successful in launching

00:21:59.640 --> 00:22:00.610
these games this year.

00:22:00.610 --> 00:22:03.210
So we've taken a lot of
learnings from you guys

00:22:03.210 --> 00:22:05.140
and really want to
share as much as we can.

00:22:05.140 --> 00:22:07.140
I'm really afraid that
we're running out of time

00:22:07.140 --> 00:22:08.910
and I think I have
to cut this short.

00:22:08.910 --> 00:22:11.550
Although I think I could stay
here for the entire afternoon.

00:22:11.550 --> 00:22:13.070
Do we have time for
questions still?

00:22:13.070 --> 00:22:13.980
OK, cool.

