For us, it was,
also, in addition

00:23:54.560 --> 00:23:57.530
to this, because it was our
next big hidden object game

00:23:57.530 --> 00:24:01.760
and we've got an
extremely loyal fan base.

00:24:01.760 --> 00:24:04.161
We knew our best
users, our VIPs,

00:24:04.161 --> 00:24:05.660
from our previous
hidden object game

00:24:05.660 --> 00:24:07.850
would play "June's
Journey" on day one.

00:24:07.850 --> 00:24:09.560
They need to have
a great experience.

00:24:09.560 --> 00:24:12.210
Therefore, things like this
weekly content production,

00:24:12.210 --> 00:24:13.400
which is crazy.

00:24:13.400 --> 00:24:15.680
Every Friday releasing
a new chapter.

00:24:15.680 --> 00:24:17.540
We wanted to have
practice in that.

00:24:17.540 --> 00:24:21.440
We wanted to have practice in
a real market, with real users,

00:24:21.440 --> 00:24:23.990
and with real customer care,
and with real social media

00:24:23.990 --> 00:24:27.440
interaction, and with
real weekly pressure,

00:24:27.440 --> 00:24:29.600
basically, on the
team, to, yes, this

00:24:29.600 --> 00:24:33.380
has to be out, to see if
it really, really works

00:24:33.380 --> 00:24:35.925
or if we would break
everything when we go global.

00:24:35.925 --> 00:24:38.300
That, in addition to what you
said on the marketing side,

00:24:38.300 --> 00:24:39.200
was important to us.

00:24:39.200 --> 00:24:40.866
SAAD CHOUDRI: The
other thing we learned

00:24:40.866 --> 00:24:43.970
was we launched tha
game, which is probably

00:24:43.970 --> 00:24:47.030
sacrilege to say in here,
but the initial binary

00:24:47.030 --> 00:24:49.449
download was 1.6 gigabytes.

00:24:49.449 --> 00:24:51.740
So we needed to make sure
that we can do that globally.

00:24:51.740 --> 00:24:53.720
In the UK, it works.

00:24:53.720 --> 00:24:57.410
That was a big thing
for us to test as well.

00:24:57.410 --> 00:24:58.940
IKY SANDORFFY: Nice.

00:24:58.940 --> 00:25:01.820
We have time for one
more quick question.

00:25:01.820 --> 00:25:02.990
First come, first served.

00:25:07.130 --> 00:25:10.540
Let me summarize with one
quick question of my own,

00:25:10.540 --> 00:25:11.590
the last one.

00:25:11.590 --> 00:25:13.100
Just a flash question.

00:25:13.100 --> 00:25:15.530
If there is one thing that
you would want this room

00:25:15.530 --> 00:25:18.650
to take away, what's the
one KPI or the one tool

00:25:18.650 --> 00:25:22.130
that the audience
should be considering

00:25:22.130 --> 00:25:23.570
when launching a new title.

00:25:23.570 --> 00:25:26.570
What's that key KPI
you're looking at?

00:25:26.570 --> 00:25:27.320
George?

00:25:27.320 --> 00:25:29.945
GEORGE ABRAMOVICI: For us, that
always has been and always will

00:25:29.945 --> 00:25:34.260
be engagement, as well
as retention rates.

00:25:34.260 --> 00:25:38.540
Understand why players
play your game, why

00:25:38.540 --> 00:25:41.260
players don't like your game.

00:25:41.260 --> 00:25:44.510
That's key to further
grow your game as well.

00:25:44.510 --> 00:25:48.020
You need to know exactly
what are the pain points

00:25:48.020 --> 00:25:52.340
and fix them as
soon as possible.

00:25:52.340 --> 00:25:54.330
Very important for
launch, I would

00:25:54.330 --> 00:25:58.610
say it's have enough content
for the most engaged players,

00:25:58.610 --> 00:26:00.410
like you were saying, as well.

00:26:00.410 --> 00:26:03.099
Don't underestimate that.

00:26:03.099 --> 00:26:05.390
Just make sure that there's
enough content for the most

00:26:05.390 --> 00:26:06.950
engaged players out there.

00:26:06.950 --> 00:26:08.330
They can be very
vocal afterwards

00:26:08.330 --> 00:26:09.869
if they run out of it, so--

00:26:09.869 --> 00:26:12.160
IKY SANDORFFY: You don't want
to get your highest value

00:26:12.160 --> 00:26:14.130
gamers getting
disappointed very quickly

00:26:14.130 --> 00:26:15.660
and having finished
the game early.

00:26:15.660 --> 00:26:17.560
GEORGE ABRAMOVICI: Absolutely

00:26:17.560 --> 00:26:18.670
IKY SANDORFFY: I've been
affected with that myself

00:26:18.670 --> 00:26:19.370
sometimes.

00:26:19.370 --> 00:26:23.864
Having reached the end
of the game too quickly.

00:26:23.864 --> 00:26:25.280
JENS BEGEMANN: In
addition to what

00:26:25.280 --> 00:26:27.847
you said, George, on
retention during soft launch.

00:26:27.847 --> 00:26:29.930
I think it's really when
you're super early stage,

00:26:29.930 --> 00:26:33.710
or early stage, and you're
doing your play testing,

00:26:33.710 --> 00:26:34.937
see excitement.

00:26:34.937 --> 00:26:36.770
If you don't see
excitement among your team,

00:26:36.770 --> 00:26:40.074
among people who play
it, very bad sign.

00:26:40.074 --> 00:26:41.490
IKY SANDORFFY:
That's a good cure.

00:26:41.490 --> 00:26:42.020
Saad.

00:26:42.020 --> 00:26:44.030
SAAD CHOUDRI: For us,
long term retention

00:26:44.030 --> 00:26:45.821
is probably the most
important thing for us

00:26:45.821 --> 00:26:46.910
to look at and for.

00:26:49.640 --> 00:26:50.750
The one issue that--

00:26:50.750 --> 00:26:52.400
we've discussed this
in this industry

00:26:52.400 --> 00:26:57.170
is funny, because 15%
D30, that is very good.

00:26:57.170 --> 00:26:58.880
Or 10% D30 would be good.

00:26:58.880 --> 00:27:01.400
That's kind of crazy to
think about your game started

00:27:01.400 --> 00:27:05.330
with 100 users and
now you've got 10.

00:27:05.330 --> 00:27:08.960
As an industry,
and as game makers,

00:27:08.960 --> 00:27:10.550
and as content
developers, we're going

00:27:10.550 --> 00:27:12.760
to need to improve
that in the future.

00:27:12.760 --> 00:27:16.250
That ought to be very difficult
to have viable business going

00:27:16.250 --> 00:27:17.851
down that route.

00:27:17.851 --> 00:27:18.850
SERGEI ZAITSEV: I agree.

00:27:18.850 --> 00:27:23.690
If it was only one advice,
just to focus a lot.

00:27:23.690 --> 00:27:28.920
Focus a lot on the product and
focus only on critical things.

00:27:28.920 --> 00:27:30.450
When you soft
launch a game, there

00:27:30.450 --> 00:27:34.340
should be only a small list
of most critical things

00:27:34.340 --> 00:27:36.320
that you should focus on.

00:27:36.320 --> 00:27:40.880
You should ruthlessly drop
everything not important

00:27:40.880 --> 00:27:42.620
and focus only on
important things.

00:27:45.290 --> 00:27:49.280
What's important is always
dependent on the game,

00:27:49.280 --> 00:27:50.140
on the context.

00:27:50.140 --> 00:27:55.430
If you have a game with amazing
graphics, and the graphics

00:27:55.430 --> 00:27:56.860
are the most important feature.

00:27:56.860 --> 00:28:00.620
So you should make
sure that this is core

00:28:00.620 --> 00:28:02.870
and you should polish it a lot.

00:28:02.870 --> 00:28:07.230
You should care less about
leagues or clans for fair game.

00:28:07.230 --> 00:28:10.940
But if it's a DVD
PUP game, then you

00:28:10.940 --> 00:28:14.180
should make sure that
PUP is pretty polished

00:28:14.180 --> 00:28:19.280
and graphic is less important.

00:28:19.280 --> 00:28:20.960
This is Playrix's way.

00:28:20.960 --> 00:28:21.800
We focus a lot.

00:28:21.800 --> 00:28:24.710
We don't do many games.

00:28:24.710 --> 00:28:27.200
For us, you will
see good results.

00:28:27.200 --> 00:28:29.340
So I advise you to try it too.

00:28:32.120 --> 00:28:34.070
IKY SANDORFFY: Content,
focus, retention.

00:28:34.070 --> 00:28:37.310
That's essentially
the key summary points

00:28:37.310 --> 00:28:39.320
that I'm getting out of here.

00:28:39.320 --> 00:28:41.240
Gentlemen, thank you
so much for coming up

00:28:41.240 --> 00:28:43.910
on stage and for agreeing to
share with the wider team.

